# TypeScript Clean Code

Use strict, explicit types at boundaries: exported functions, public methods, DTOs, API clients, repositories, and shared contracts should have clear return types.

Avoid `any`. Use `unknown` only at real external boundaries, then narrow it immediately. Avoid type assertions unless a mapper or framework boundary makes the invariant obvious.

Model states with unions and `as const` values instead of loose strings. Prefer discriminated unions when a value can be in distinct states.

Make invalid states hard to represent. Keep nullability explicit and do not use optional fields where the wire contract really returns `null`.

Prefer `type` for object shapes and `interface` for framework contracts or extension points. Keep domain/application types separate from Prisma types and HTTP DTO classes.

Use descriptive names and the same vocabulary for the same concept across API, web, and shared contracts.

Keep functions focused. Extract helpers when a block mixes validation, persistence, mapping, and presentation concerns.

Keep parameter lists short. If a function needs more than a few values, accept a typed options object with names that explain the call site.

Do not swallow errors. If an error is intentionally converted to `null`, `false`, or a domain outcome, keep that conversion local and obvious.

Use type-only imports for types and avoid importing framework or database types into shared/browser code.

Dates crossing HTTP boundaries are ISO strings. `Date` objects should stay inside server-side infrastructure/application code unless explicitly converted.
